00:17:59,360 --> 00:18:02,079
You 'll be able to get out.
No, it's... (SIGHS)

263
00:18:04,440 --> 00:18:09,440
Yep. (GRUNTS)
Thanks, Pop. This is perfect.

264
00:18:09,440 --> 00:18:13,560
Hey, honey, get in the bathtub, OK?
And then we'll have dinner.

265
00:18:13,560 --> 00:18:15,073
OK, Mom!

266
00:18:19,280 --> 00:18:20,920
What's that?

267
00:18:20,920 --> 00:18:24,480
Adam's file. Take a look.

268
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:26,152
I'll think about it.

269
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:41,276
(VOICES WHISPER)

270
00:18:56,760 --> 00:18:58,193
(BONES CRUNCH)

271
00:19:22,680 --> 00:19:26,120
ADAM: I don't seem to have much time
for God nowadays, Doctor.

272
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:29,560
It seems to work both ways.

273
00:19:29,560 --> 00:19:32,640
Hows about you? Got your faith?

274
00:19:32,640 --> 00:19:35,600
DR HARDING: My daughter
lost her husband not too long ago.

275
00:19:35,600 --> 00:19:37,320
He was a good, good man

276
00:19:37,320 --> 00:19:40,680
and he was murdered
for no reason at all.

277
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:43,120
Murdered?
Mm-hm.

278
00:19:43,120 --> 00:19:45,480
So I find it kind of hard to believe

279
00:19:45,480 --> 00:19:47,311
in a God that could hurt my daughter...

280
00:19:48,880 --> 00:19:52,160
...is Adam there?

281
00:19:52,160 --> 00:19:55,920
(SOUTHERN ACCENT) I'm sorry,
Dr Harding. I'm the only one here.

282
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:58,920
(GRUNTS AND GROANS)

283
00:19:58,920 --> 00:20:02,356
(SQUELCHING AND CRUNCHING)

284
00:20:24,160 --> 00:20:25,720
MAN: Little CC.

285
00:20:25,720 --> 00:20:28,800
Hey, Charlie. You look terrible.

286
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:30,520
Well, thank you.

287
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:32,840
A course of antibiotics, I'll be fine.

288
00:20:32,840 --> 00:20:35,360
Alright.
To what do I owe the pleasure?

289
00:20:35,360 --> 00:20:36,840
Um, Adam Saber.

290
00:20:36,840 --> 00:20:40,760
I want to know how he came to you
and why you dumped him on my father.

291
00:20:40,760 --> 00:20:44,080
The police found him laying in the street.

292
00:20:44,080 --> 00:20:49,440
He didn't appear intoxicated.
Claimed he wasn't able to walk.

293
00:20:49,440 --> 00:20:51,800
Gave his name as David Bernburg.

294
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:53,680
By the time I examined him,

295
00:20:53,680 --> 00:20:57,680
he was up on his feet,
calling himself Adam Saber,

296
00:20:57,680 --> 00:21:01,600
said he had no idea
how he got to the hospital.

297
00:21:01,600 --> 00:21:03,600
Well, I thought of
your father immediately.

298
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:05,960
Well, yeah, sure.

299
00:21:05,960 --> 00:21:11,353
Um, have you ever had a patient
who was colourblind in just one eye?

300
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:14,280
No. Why?

301
00:21:14,280 --> 00:21:16,400
I was just thinking it might explain...

302
00:21:16,400 --> 00:21:18,360
Never mind.

303
00:21:18,360 --> 00:21:20,640
How's Sammy?
She's great.

304
00:21:20,640 --> 00:21:22,200
Soccer-crazy.

305
00:21:22,200 --> 00:21:24,840
There are tryouts at the school
this Friday. You should come.

306
00:21:24,840 --> 00:21:26,920
I'd like that.
Good.

307
00:21:26,920 --> 00:21:31,480
Um, can I get a copy of his hospital file?

308
00:21:31,480 --> 00:21:34,800
I'll fax it this afternoon.
Thank you.

309
00:21:34,800 --> 00:21:36,960
Take care of yourself, alright?
Yeah.

310
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:38,640
I will. You take care of that kid.

311
00:21:38,640 --> 00:21:41,120
Yeah. Always.

312
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:43,440
Um, does Ellie still work in radiology?

313
00:21:43,440 --> 00:21:45,840
Yeah, but she's up
on the third floor now.

314
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:47,840
Alright. Thanks again.

315
00:21:47,840 --> 00:21:49,273
'Bye.

316
00:21:52,560 --> 00:21:55,518
(COUGHS)

317
00:22:01,200 --> 00:22:04,320
Is it possible that
when he wrenches his neck,

318
00:22:04,320 --> 00:22:06,000
he's compressing,
decompressing a nerve

319
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:09,200
and causing some kind
of temporary paralysis?

320
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:11,320
Look.

321
00:22:11,320 --> 00:22:15,280
This X-ray - the third, the fourth,
the fifth vertebrae...

322
00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:17,880
Fused.
Mmm.

323
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:20,520
So we're looking at X-rays here
of two different people.

324
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:22,640
Two different people.

325
00:22:22,640 --> 00:22:26,160
It's a hoax - a guy, the doctor.

326
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:28,280
The doctor?
Sure.

327
00:22:28,280 --> 00:22:32,796
How well do you know him?
Well, some days, not at all.

328
00:22:46,880 --> 00:22:49,440
Gets under your skin, doesn't he?

329
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:52,591
These aren't his films. They can't be.

330
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:57,280
Isn't it possible
that what you 're looking at

331
00:22:57,280 --> 00:22:59,200
is actually what you 're seeing?

332
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:02,560
No, because this is not possible.

333
00:23:02,560 --> 00:23:04,040
Adam is the real deal.
No.

334
00:23:04,040 --> 00:23:05,520
He is a desperately ill young man,

335
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:07,880
but he's fully aware of David
and all of David's actions.

336
00:23:07,880 --> 00:23:10,400
David is pure invention
and I'll prove it to you.

337
00:23:10,400 --> 00:23:15,480
You know what? We haven't had
dinner together in over a month.

338
00:23:15,480 --> 00:23:17,280
Well, you 're coming to Easter,
aren't you?

339
00:23:17,280 --> 00:23:19,440
Uh-huh.

340
00:23:19,440 --> 00:23:21,040
Do you want me to bring anything?

341
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:22,712
Just your delightful self.

342
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:28,760
That's my girl.
Yeah.

343
00:23:28,760 --> 00:23:30,955
Thanks.
Thank you. (CHUCKLES)

344
00:23:35,640 --> 00:23:38,393
(MUTTERS) OK, what name?

345
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:46,920
So, David Bernburg,
Shadywood High School, Shadywood.

346
00:23:46,920 --> 00:23:49,354
Shadywood.

347
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:51,355
(GASPS)

348
00:23:54,800 --> 00:23:57,600
Sorry, Doctor. Scared you a little
right there, huh?

349
00:23:57,600 --> 00:23:59,320
Yeah, a little bit. Yeah.

350
00:23:59,320 --> 00:24:01,440
Listen, uh, I didn't want you to leave

351
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,240
without having a chance
to say thank you.

352
00:24:03,240 --> 00:24:04,878
For what?

353
00:24:06,520 --> 00:24:08,511
For trying to help.

354
00:24:11,080 --> 00:24:12,559
Thanks.
You 're welcome.

355
00:24:15,600 --> 00:24:18,068
(STARTS CAR)

356
00:24:28,480 --> 00:24:32,000
Excuse me. I'm looking for yearbooks.

357
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:33,480
Second aisle down to the back.

358
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:35,680
But you best be quick.
I'm locking up in 10 minutes.

359
00:24:35,680 --> 00:24:37,671
No, I'll be quick. I promise.

360
00:24:40,040 --> 00:24:41,473
OK.

361
00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:29,756
WOMAN: Are you almost done?

362
00:25:32,040 --> 00:25:34,190
Um, I'll be done in a minute.

363
00:25:59,320 --> 00:26:01,311
(GASPS)

364
00:26:06,960 --> 00:26:11,120
CARA: Matthew, Mark, Luke and John
Bless the bed that I lay on

365
00:26:11,120 --> 00:26:15,680
Bless me as they lay me down to sleep
I give myself to God to keep

366
00:26:15,680 --> 00:26:20,280
Five little angels round my bed
One to the foot and one to the head

367
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:25,877
One to sing and one to pray
And one to take my sins away.

368
00:26:34,280 --> 00:26:36,316
Amen.

369
00:26:43,560 --> 00:26:45,710
She doesn't mean it.

370
00:26:47,200 --> 00:26:48,758
Right?

371
00:26:59,400 --> 00:27:01,120
(RINGING TONE ON PHONE)

372
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:03,800
(MAN COUGHS) Hello.
Charlie?

373
00:27:03,800 --> 00:27:06,600
(CONTINUES COUGHING)
Oh, little CC.

374
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:08,560
You sound terrible.

375
00:27:08,560 --> 00:27:11,640
Listen, listen. Can I bring you anything?

376
00:27:11,640 --> 00:27:13,960
Uh, no. I've got soup.

377
00:27:13,960 --> 00:27:18,600
And, um, that antibiotic's
about to kick in.

378
00:27:18,600 --> 00:27:24,240
I hate to ask, but you never
faxed me Adam Saber's file.

379
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:26,920
Oh, I'm sorry. Is first thing alright?

380
00:27:26,920 --> 00:27:29,559
Yeah, yeah, of course.
Just get some rest, OK?

381
00:27:30,600 --> 00:27:32,440
I will.

382
00:27:32,440 --> 00:27:34,400
(COUGHS) See you soon.

383
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:36,320
OK. Feel better.

384
00:27:36,320 --> 00:27:39,278
(COUGHS AND HACKS)

385
00:27:45,640 --> 00:27:47,995
(GAGS AND RETCHES)

386
00:27:53,440 --> 00:27:56,432
(GENTLE EERIE MUSIC)

387
00:29:19,040 --> 00:29:21,998
(RATTLING)

388
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:36,120
Excuse me.

389
00:29:36,120 --> 00:29:38,759
Do you know the way
to the Quarry House?

390
00:29:39,800 --> 00:29:41,233
(CLICKS TONGUE)

391
00:29:47,920 --> 00:29:49,831
I don't know how I got to the hospital.

392
00:29:50,880 --> 00:29:53,280
I have no idea
how I got to bed last night.

393
00:29:53,280 --> 00:29:56,120
You know, I just wake up in my room
and I don't remember nothing.

394
00:29:56,120 --> 00:29:57,720
(CLICKS)

395
00:29:57,720 --> 00:30:00,720
DR HARDING: The nurses
helped you into your bed.

396
00:30:00,720 --> 00:30:02,880
Was I awake?

397
00:30:02,880 --> 00:30:05,110
In a matter of speaking.

398
00:30:39,320 --> 00:30:41,914
(KNOCKS)

399
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:47,351
Hello?

400
00:31:43,520 --> 00:31:46,478
(WOMAN HUMS SONG SOFTLY)

401
00:32:03,960 --> 00:32:05,680
They're ruined, aren't they?

402
00:32:05,680 --> 00:32:09,320
I... I'm sorry. I knocked at the front door.

403
00:32:09,320 --> 00:32:12,360
I was...
I found them this morning.

404
00:32:12,360 --> 00:32:15,200
They must have been
in water for weeks.

405
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:19,560
All that music, all that life, all gone.

406
00:32:19,560 --> 00:32:23,400
I think... I think some of it
can be saved, actually.

407
00:32:23,400 --> 00:32:25,709
Well, there's always hope.

408
00:32:26,760 --> 00:32:28,720
Now, who are you?

409
00:32:28,720 --> 00:32:31,240
I'm looking for David Bernburg.

410
00:32:31,240 --> 00:32:33,360
David?
Yeah.

411
00:32:33,360 --> 00:32:35,828
You 're standing on him, aren't you?

412
00:32:51,040 --> 00:32:53,679
Well, it happens around
this time of year -

413
00:32:54,720 --> 00:32:56,280
some local reporter

414
00:32:56,280 --> 00:32:59,280
inevitably stumbles onto
a story in the archives

415
00:32:59,280 --> 00:33:03,640
and tries to resurrect it
as a cautionary tale.

416
00:33:03,640 --> 00:33:06,029
Are you talking about David's accident?

417
00:33:07,240 --> 00:33:09,037
No, my dear.

418
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:13,310
His murder.

419
00:33:20,600 --> 00:33:22,640
How did his accident happen?

420
00:33:22,640 --> 00:33:24,560
He fell.

421
00:33:24,560 --> 00:33:28,440
Wet leaves on stone steps.

422
00:33:28,440 --> 00:33:33,195
And just like that
his life had to begin again.

423
00:33:36,520 --> 00:33:40,115
But he accepted his fate
with such nobility.

424
00:33:41,160 --> 00:33:43,680
For three years,

425
00:33:43,680 --> 00:33:48,595
David showed the world how brightly
the Holy Spirit shone within him.

426
00:33:50,800 --> 00:33:55,715
But then... David lost his way.

427
00:34:00,680 --> 00:34:03,800
He found a doctor in the city

428
00:34:03,800 --> 00:34:09,352
who was experimenting with spinal
replacement or some such nonsense.

429
00:34:10,520 --> 00:34:13,400
David came to believe
that this practitioner

430
00:34:13,400 --> 00:34:16,233
would one day give him back his legs.

431
00:34:17,280 --> 00:34:18,760
It seemed as if every month,

432
00:34:18,760 --> 00:34:22,355
he'd ride into the city on the bus
with hope in his eyes...

433
00:34:23,480 --> 00:34:28,600
...only to be injected and sliced open

434
00:34:28,600 --> 00:34:32,673
and return broken-hearted.

435
00:34:33,720 --> 00:34:36,800
And then one month he left home

436
00:34:36,800 --> 00:34:39,439
and never returned.

437
00:34:42,200 --> 00:34:45,795
It was one week later
when they found his remains.

438
00:34:46,920 --> 00:34:52,472
He'd... been taken into the woods
and abused.

439
00:34:53,520 --> 00:34:55,033
Tortured.

440
00:34:56,240 --> 00:34:58,834
Can you imagine?

441
00:35:00,880 --> 00:35:04,560
David sitting there, watching,

442
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:06,680
unable to fight back,

443
00:35:06,680 --> 00:35:10,720
watching as they did those
unspeakable things to him?

444
00:35:10,720 --> 00:35:13,240
I... I cannot. I...

445
00:35:13,240 --> 00:35:15,595
And I pray you never will.

446
00:35:19,640 --> 00:35:22,600
David turned his back on God

447
00:35:22,600 --> 00:35:25,637
and looked to science for his answers.

448
00:35:26,960 --> 00:35:30,270
The Lord told us quite plainly.

449
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:36,515
"Wane not, thy faith in me."

450
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:47,758
(PEOPLE CHATTER QUIETLY)

451
00:35:52,640 --> 00:35:56,680
Hey, Art. I'll have a cup of coffee
and some of that apple pie, huh?

452
00:35:56,680 --> 00:36:00,200
Hi, honey bun.
Did you have a good time, hmm?

453
00:36:00,200 --> 00:36:02,280
No. We had a bird funeral.

454
00:36:02,280 --> 00:36:05,160
Great. Great.
Mmm, yeah.

455
00:36:05,160 --> 00:36:08,160
Well, do you want to pick out a treat
while I talk to Grandpa?

456
00:36:08,160 --> 00:36:09,912
OK, go ahead.

457
00:36:13,240 --> 00:36:15,720
What's the fundamental difference

458
00:36:15,720 --> 00:36:19,760
between a disassociated personality
and a delusional one?

459
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:21,240
No hello?

460
00:36:21,240 --> 00:36:23,680
'Cause I have something.
Yeah?

461
00:36:23,680 --> 00:36:30,520
OK, so the real David Bernburg
was born on February 5, 1963.

462
00:36:30,520 --> 00:36:35,200
He slipped and broke his back
in November of 1979.

463
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:39,160
In April of 1982, he was murdered.

464
00:36:39,160 --> 00:36:42,840
Now, while every local TV station
and newspaper

465
00:36:42,840 --> 00:36:46,360
was recounting the details
of his horrific death,

466
00:36:46,360 --> 00:36:50,720
your Adam Saber was six years old,
his mother had just died

467
00:36:50,720 --> 00:36:53,600
and he'd been placed in
the first of several foster homes.

468
00:36:53,600 --> 00:36:56,880
His escape was this...
this macabre murder.

469
00:36:56,880 --> 00:36:59,920
Now, everything
that Adam knew of David

470
00:36:59,920 --> 00:37:03,440
he would have gleaned
from the media, right?

471
00:37:03,440 --> 00:37:07,080
OK, well, say that I agree with these...

472
00:37:07,080 --> 00:37:09,480
...somewhat shaky assumptions.

473
00:37:09,480 --> 00:37:13,520
Why would Adam create a delusion?

474
00:37:13,520 --> 00:37:16,160
Give me your wallet.

475
00:37:16,160 --> 00:37:18,196
Any wallet will do?
Mm-hm.

476
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:21,320
(CHUCKLES)
Alright.

477
00:37:21,320 --> 00:37:25,440
So why do you carry
this picture of Mom?

478
00:37:25,440 --> 00:37:27,000
To remind me of her.

479
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,960
Mm-hm, and experience the positive
effects that these memories evoke.

480
00:37:29,960 --> 00:37:31,440
Yeah.
Yes.

481
00:37:31,440 --> 00:37:34,880
Now, if this picture existed
but you had no awareness of it,

482
00:37:34,880 --> 00:37:37,320
would you still be able
to benefit from its existence?

483
00:37:37,320 --> 00:37:39,040
I suppose not, no.

484
00:37:39,040 --> 00:37:40,520
Oh, OK.

485
00:37:40,520 --> 00:37:43,000
So I believe, as a child,

486
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:46,520
Adam Saber began carrying around
a mental picture of David

487
00:37:46,520 --> 00:37:50,480
so that no matter where he went,
no matter how horrific things became,

488
00:37:50,480 --> 00:37:52,440
there was always someone
who had it worse -

489
00:37:52,440 --> 00:37:54,320
David Bernburg
who was tortured to death

490
00:37:54,320 --> 00:37:56,200
by Satan-worshipping
mountain witches.

491
00:37:56,200 --> 00:37:58,960
But to benefit from this mental image,

492
00:37:58,960 --> 00:38:01,040
he must be fully aware of it

493
00:38:01,040 --> 00:38:04,396
and therefore
cannot be disassociated.

494
00:38:06,080 --> 00:38:09,959
That is a very compelling diagnosis.
Thank you very much.

495
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:12,760
How are you gonna prove it?

496
00:38:12,760 --> 00:38:17,760
Oh, oh, Dad, I'm not gonna prove it.

497
00:38:17,760 --> 00:38:19,880
I'm gonna cure it.

498
00:38:19,880 --> 00:38:22,838
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

499
00:38:24,880 --> 00:38:26,800
Hello, Mrs Bernburg.

500
00:38:26,800 --> 00:38:30,480
Thank you again for agreeing
to help me with this.

501
00:38:30,480 --> 00:38:36,240
I wanted to tell you that, um, Adam has
created an impersonation of your son.

502
00:38:36,240 --> 00:38:40,120
I, um... I don't want you to be alarmed.

503
00:38:40,120 --> 00:38:44,520
I've raised three boys
and said prayers upon their graves.

504
00:38:44,520 --> 00:38:46,240
Not much alarms me.

505
00:38:46,240 --> 00:38:49,400
Thank you. I do appreciate it.

506
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:50,992
Here's... this is Adam now.

507
00:38:53,080 --> 00:38:55,120
Hello, Adam.
Hey.

508
00:38:55,120 --> 00:38:57,315
This is Dita Bernburg.

509
00:38:58,680 --> 00:39:01,717
Is the name familiar to you at all?
Nope.

510
00:39:04,040 --> 00:39:08,960
(SIGHS) Er, her son David
was murdered 25 years ago.

511
00:39:08,960 --> 00:39:10,678
Shit.

512
00:39:12,200 --> 00:39:13,920
I'm sorry.

513
00:39:13,920 --> 00:39:16,360
You may have heard of it.

514
00:39:16,360 --> 00:39:18,120
It was in the papers.

515
00:39:18,120 --> 00:39:22,671
25 years ago? I was, like, 6 years old.

516
00:39:23,960 --> 00:39:25,871
I didn't read the papers much.
